I wanted to share the approach used to generate CEL expressions for fields that belong to arrays in our schema. Since our schema paths are flattened and arrays are represented using "[]", we can reliably construct CEL expressions using simple parsing and string manipulation.
Key Idea
In the flattened schema path, the "[]" marker indicates that the field is an array. Everything that appears after "[]" represents the structure of the array element. Therefore, the rule must be applied to each element of the array using the CEL "all()" iterator.
For example:
Flattened schema path:Header.SystemIdentification[].Identification.Scheme.COLUMN_LONG_1
Meaning:SystemIdentification is an array, and the rule should be applied to each element inside that array.
The corresponding CEL path becomes:
message.Header.SystemIdentification.all(x, x.Identification.Scheme.COLUMN_LONG_1)
Here "x" represents the iterator variable for each element of the array.
---
CEL Structure
CEL requires array validations to follow this pattern:
array.all(iterator, condition)
Example:
message.Header.SystemIdentification.all(x,x.Identification.Scheme.COLUMN_LONG_1 < 100)
---
Algorithm Used
1. Split the flattened schema path using "".""2. Detect any part containing "[]"3. For each array level:   - Remove "[]"   - Generate ".all(iterator,"4. Continue building the inner path using the iterator variable5. Close the parentheses for each array level
Iterator sequence used:
x → first arrayy → second arrayz → third array
---
Java Implementation
private String buildCelPath(String path) {
    String[] parts = path.split("\\.");    String[] iterators = {"x", "y", "z", "a", "b"};
    StringBuilder cel = new StringBuilder("message");    int arrayLevel = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < parts.length; i++) {
        String part = parts[i];
        if (part.contains("[]")) {
            String field = part.replace("[]", "");            String iterator = iterators[arrayLevel];
            cel.append(".")               .append(field)               .append(".all(")               .append(iterator)               .append(", ")               .append(iterator);
            arrayLevel++;
        } else {
            cel.append(".").append(part);        }    }
    for (int i = 0; i < arrayLevel; i++) {        cel.append(")");    }
    return cel.toString();}
